fields.descriptive_line: Build-O-Fun, set no. 101, from Tupperware Toys, London, 1968.
fields.physical_description:
[Box] Colour printed box lid, with ecru background, logo and photograph of the toy on the lid, illustrations of the pieces and building ideas on the sides. Plain box base, with adhesive taped edges.
[Red pieces] Red plastic squares with protruding edges and eight pins at the back, designed to connect to other pieces from the set.
[Blue pieces] Blue plastic squares with protruding edges and eight pins at the back, designed to connect to other pieces from the set.
[White connector pieces] White plastic rectangular cuboid, with grooves down each long edge for connecting other pieces from the set, which create an 'x' shape when seen from the end.
[Yellow wheel connectors] Yellow plastic circular piece, with central square shaped hole with three pins designed to connect to other pieces in the set. 
[Black wheels] Black plastic circles with central circular hole, and 12 pins at the back for connecting to other pieces in the set. 
[Leaflet] Colour printed paper leaflet, folded in three lengthways, with photographs of the toy and instructions on a beige background.

fields.public_access_description: This construction set was created by the Tupperware company, an organisation more famous for their airtight food storage containers. The  Tupperware sales market was based on sales parties, held by women and directed at other women. Developed in the 1950s, this strategy was aimed primarily at housewives and thus branching into a range of toys to be sold at these parties was an obvious development. The hygienic aspect of the toys was one of the main features promoted, as this was one of the features of Tupperware's kitchenware, an association with keeping food fresh. This particular toy was a construction set made of parts in four different styles that could be linked to produce many different vehicles and play sets: examples on the leaflet include trucks, furniture and even a movie camera.
